datasource: Almkvist, Herman. 1881. Die Bischari-Sprache Tu:-Bed'a:wiye in Nordost-Afrika (beschreibend und vergleichend dargestellet). Nova Acta Regiae Societatis Scientiarum Upsalensis. Serie Tertia 11. Uppsala: Kaiserliche Akademie der Wissenschaften.
datasourceNotes: The verbal paradigms are mostly taken from the sections V. and VI, pp. 162-238, #231-326; the stemClass values have been chosen in such a way as to provide maximum isomorphism with the sequence of the paradigms in Almkvists grammar if the AAMA-application Source Table columns are arranged in the order: Source Pos Conjclass Rootclass Stemclass Lexeme Derivedstem Polarity Tam]. Almkvist gives a very large number of paradigms (more than 500) with only one form; for the moment these paradigms are grouped under the rubric 'specialPdgms'. // In order to avoid confusion and for ease of comparison,  what Almkvist calls Aorist is here termed Future. Almkvists informants were apparently unaware of the second past tense frequently termed Aorist in the other varieties of cushitic beja currently recorded in AAMA (cf. Appleyard2007, p. 468). Note that Alm has Person3 negative imperatives which seem distinct from optatives (and jussives?). Note also that Almkvist calls both the T-stem and the M stem Passive, and  that a SM seems to exist.

Vowels.inventory: i e a o u; ī ē ā ō ū

geodemoTXT: cushitic beja is a closely related group of language varieties and dialects spoken in the Red Sea coastal and hill regions in Sudan, Eritrea, and Egypt by more than a million individuals. The Northern-most representative of cushitic beja is documented here, that of the Bishari in Aswan and Sudan, studied by Herman Almkvist (1881) in one of the earliest monographs dedicated to a variety of cushitic beja.
